### Retry/backoff strategy comparison table

Retries must be implemented carefully because careless retries can amplify outages and create ŌĆ£retry storms.ŌĆØ ŅłĆciteŅłéturn12search4Ņłü Exponential backoff is a standard strategy, and jitter is recommended to prevent synchronized retries. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn12search0Ņłü

| Strategy | How it works | Pros | Cons | When to use for FLHSMV |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Immediate retry | Retry instantly on failure ŅłĆciteŅłéturn12search0Ņłü | Lowest latency | Can hammer FLHSMV; worsens outages | Almost never; only for a single retry on connection reset |
| Fixed delay | Retry after constant delay | Simple | Can still synchronize; slow recovery tuning | Minor transient network errors when rate limits unlikely |
| Exponential backoff | Delay doubles each failure (1s,2s,4sŌĆ”) ŅłĆciteŅłéturn12search0Ņłü | Reduces load during failure; standard resilience | Without caps, can grow too large; without jitter can synchronize | Default for 5xx/timeout failures |
| Exponential backoff + jitter | Backoff plus random spread to avoid storms ŅłĆciteŅłéturn12search0Ņłéturn12search4Ņłü | Best overall behavior under partial outage | Slightly more logic | Recommended default for FLHSMV |
| Retry with fallback | Retry, then degrade gracefully ŅłĆciteŅłéturn12search0Ņłéturn12search3Ņłü | Avoids total failure | Must define fallback behavior | If scraper is blocked, fall back to replay harness or last cached ingest window |

### Dedupe approach comparison table

The difference between ŌĆ£stable pipelineŌĆØ and ŌĆ£spam/flood/missing crashesŌĆØ is often dedupe design. Database-enforced uniqueness is a strong baseline (UNIQUE constraint or unique index). ŅłĆciteŅłéturn15search0Ņłéturn15search4Ņłü UPSERT then becomes your idempotent write primitive. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn15search1Ņłü

| Approach | Dedupe key | Pros | Cons | Best use |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Natural source ID | `source_report_id` from FLHSMV | Strongest if stable | Not always available; sometimes changes | If FLHSMV exposes a stable report number |
| Payload hash | `sha256(raw_payload)` | Easy; detects exact duplicates | Breaks if same crash updates fields; minor HTML differences create new hashes | Good as secondary constraint for raw snapshots |
| Composite location/time | `(occurred_at_utc, lat, lng, county)` | Works when no ID | Collisions; needs careful rounding | If FLHSMV provides time + location reliably |
| Fuzzy matching | heuristic match across rows | Handles messy data | Complex and error-prone | Only if FLHSMV is extremely inconsistent |
| Stateful watermark | ŌĆ£Anything after last_seenŌĆØ | Efficient | Misses late-arriving updates | Use only for fetching; still enforce DB dedupe |

